  "shortBio": "Gearlings of Alloy Ruins, titled “Cogpath Softling,” are protective alloy-touched Riftlings—living metal with organic pulse. In the wild they stay protective, living metal with organic pulse, and attentive to micro-changes in copper bloom and oil-sweet moss. Favorites include Alloy Moss. Keepers know them by soft chuff and the scent of copper bloom and oil-sweet moss.",
  "standardBio": "Gearling, titled among keepers as “Scrapgarden Tinker,” carries inventive purpose in every movement. Native to Alloy Ruins, the species mends through copper bloom and oil-sweet moss, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a protective individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Alloy Moss eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Gearling silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their spatial memory that rivals scout maps makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Cog Strike, reflects a life shaped by Alloy Ruins more than by arena ambition. Collectors sometimes treat them as ornaments. Wild Gearlings are social strategists, not decorations. Young Gearlings practice Cog Strike as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Gearlings first condensed from residual gearsong along the living edges of Alloy Ruins after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where copper bloom and oil-sweet moss gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Gearling returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Gearlings as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Gearling into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Gearling care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Alloy Ruins still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Gearlings often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is protective at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are living metal with organic pulse, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through soft chirps and affinity flickers. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as spatial memory that rivals scout maps. They sleep in moss cups and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Gearlings act as seed dispersers of calm within Alloy Ruins. Allies often include Ironbloom and Scrapfinch; rivalries with Kelpwisp and Staticat are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. An old keeper journal swears a Gearling refused to leave an injured stranger until dawn warmth returned. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Collectors sometimes treat them as ornaments. Wild Gearlings are social strategists, not decorations. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: When deeply bonded, a Gearling shares short dream-images of places it has never physically visited.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like frosted pearls veined with alloy light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor clever disruption, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Gearling is a living chapter of Alloy Ruins. Feed it Alloy Moss, respect its protective tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Gearling bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
